segments.text: to people in the front seat heading out to the airport?
I got to the airport.
And the first thing I better do is make sure that the people at the airport had confirmed my tickets, my change of flight.
And so I got in that line.
And the Chinese are not too good about fast, friendly service.
So I must have waited in that line for about an hour.
There was one man and his wife from our U.S. State Department who were out there.
The wife's mother had been visiting in Beijing and was supposed to stay on longer, but had decided with what had happened, she wanted to go back home.
And I couldn't believe this husband and wife.
They were telling me, oh, you know, it's mother-in-law.
She's just, you know, blowing this all out of proportion.
And, you know, nothing really serious has happened here.
And I thought, this is our State Department.
I was able to confirm my flights.
They had me down for the next morning or the next day.
I looked at the board of other options of flights to see if there was anything else that was going down.
And about the only option that I had was a flight that was leaving that evening, going to Tehran.
And of course, Ayatollah Khomeini had just died recently, too.
So I figured that was probably the place I'd rather be better off in Beijing than I would be in Tehran.
So there really weren't any other options.
I found United Airlines.
They got a little office that's downstairs in the basement.
Because they only fly in a couple of times a week.
It's not staffed all the time.
Which airline was it?
It was United Airlines.
That's what the kids were going to fly out on.
They were going to come into Beijing on.
And I had flown in on.
We were going to fly from Hong Kong to Tokyo and back to the US on them.

There was a janitor down there, fortunately he spoke a little bit of English, and there was a sign on the board saying that the flight had been delayed, and it wasn't going to get in until Tuesday morning.
The flight your kids were supposed to be on?
They were supposed to be on, right.
He couldn't add anything else to that, and I thought, well, if it's open early enough in the morning, I'll check and see if that's possible.
It turned out that flight ended up being canceled, and they were going to come in.
I had my bags, I went up, and there were, I guess, about 200 of us who had done the same thing as I had.
So, it's a pretty big airport, so it really wasn't very crowded.
How big?
Can you give us an idea of size?
As big as one of the terminals?
It's about the size of one of the terminals at Houston and Continental.
on not the different corridors that go out to the planes, just one level of where you check in and your bags are.
And one Chinese student who was going over to Germany came over and started a conversation with me.
And he was from Shanghai and was
trying to get out before everything completely fell apart.
But mostly kept to myself.
Everybody had some food that they had bought at various types of events, so I ate a little bit and ended up sleeping on top of a desk where you go into for the customs inspection.
I was still, I had, after I had checked and made sure that
My tickets were okay.
There is a hotel that they had built that was out right near the airport.

There were still cabs coming in at the airport, so I went out and got one of the cabs there to take me to this hotel to see if they had a room for the night, because I figured, of course, the worst, I could walk the next morning, because it was maybe half a mile, three-quarters of a mile.
They took me there.
That hotel was all full.
And they suggested I go into Toledo.
And I said, no, I don't want to go in any closer to town.
So there was a cab that was there going back to the airport.
It already had three Chinese in it.
And so the trunk was pretty well filled.
But the guy, for a reasonable price, was willing to take me there.
And he did.
He got me back to the airport.
I spent the night at the airport.
The next morning, some more people started arriving because there were two flights that I was on, and then there were some flights later on that were leaving.
I was concerned about them perhaps closing down the airport, but they didn't.
Getting on an airplane is not an only thing in China.
One of the things that I was concerned about were the customs people and going through customs because I had a roll of film
that I'd taken out of my camera, the one that I'd taken the pictures the night before, and I was concerned if I got caught with those on me that that could create some problems.
But I had mixed it in with the other touristy roles that I'd taken.
Of course, in China, whether you're innocent or guilty, it doesn't make a difference.
If the government wants to get you, they'll just make up anything that they want to.
It's not proving innocence or guilt.
But I had put that in there.
And as it turned out, the customs people never showed up.
Or if they did, they came later on in the day.
But first of all, you have to go through this line.
And the customs people are supposed to look at your bags.
Well, they weren't there.
So we just went on through there.
And then you've got to show your tickets to the people and check your bags.
But you also have to get this little stamp
I said, departure tax stamp, separate.
There's a separate little booth that you've got to go to.
Well, I didn't know which one you had to go to first.
So I got in line for the booth thing, and the people were taking a lot.
It seemed like they should have already been there, because they were already checking some people in.
But I went with this one guy.
He said, you know, if you'll give me the money, I'll get the tax point, the stamp point.
You can go ahead and get in line.
So I said, well.
you know, I'll do that.
It wasn't all that much money.
And he got it for me and gave it to me.
And I had to go, because there were two flights, I had to go around behind where this booth was and get in this other line that was packed with people.
And there were all kinds of people who didn't have tickets who were trying to get on this plane and that.
And they don't really have the concept of a line.
You wait, you turn the line.
You just
It's everybody for himself, and you've got to just jockey for position and protect your own position.

Well, I finally got up to the front, and I showed them my tickets, and they accepted them, and they sent my, well, the belt that they have there to take the bags down to the basement where they load the things, it broke down.
It wasn't working, so people were just literally climbing up on their stack of their bags on this belt, trying to get theirs up closer to the front so that it would go down,
I kept my carry on my handbag with me that had the porn stuff in it and went ahead and went out to the waiting area.
And the pilot showed up.
We got on the plane.
We left.
It took us about 20 minutes to get to Tangier.
I was concerned there because this was another chance for them to decide
This was getting later in the morning, getting around noon, you know, that they were going to shut everything down.
We got off the plane.
We were supposed to be there for an hour.
When we landed, they made us all get off because there were some Chinese who weren't going on.
They were getting on Tianjin.
There were some people who were continuing on.
There were some new people who were going to get off.
They made all of us get off.
And I started talking with a man and his wife and their two kids.
They were...
living in Beijing, outside of Beijing, north of Beijing, he was there setting up a poultry farm for poultry, chicken.
And, you know, they were leaving.
They really didn't want to leave.
They were concerned about their friends who were back, but talk to them.
And I was getting concerned because it
Took longer than an hour, an hour and a half.
We were getting there in two hours.
We were sitting there, we were supposed to be there for an hour.
And I was afraid maybe they decided they were going to shut down all the airports.
Finally got back on the plane and took off and landed in Hong Kong Tuesday afternoon.
And once I got in Hong Kong, then I felt safe.
Of course, Hong Kong was having some demonstrations.
As a matter of fact, I was concerned when I checked into the hotel.
Because I was there earlier, I wasn't supposed to be there until Sunday.
I went to the hotel that I had made reservations for.
But they weren't sure they were going to have a room or not.
I got there about 3 in the afternoon.
They told me to come back in an hour.
And that's what everybody's supposed to be checking if you're not.
And I ended up being able to get a room there.
Asked them how long it would take me to get to the airport the next day.
And they said, well, you better leave early.
You better leave before 8, even though my plane was going to leave until 11.
because they were expecting a big demonstration of three fourths of a million people, they would clog up the streets.
So I called my wife, let her know that I had gotten out of Beijing.
You had no difficulty in making that call out of Hong Kong.
At the airport in Beijing, there were no telephones.
They had some telephone booths, but there weren't any telephones in there.
So there was no way to call out from the airport to let her know that I'd gotten that far.
But when I called her, you know, let her know that everything was okay.
And then got a good night's sleep and then left on Wednesday, left Hong Kong on Wednesday to go to Tokyo and then back.
And Tokyo to Houston?
Well, to San Francisco and then to Houston.

okay um i have like two questions i'd like to ask one if you could do the trip over again would there be any one thing that you wished you had made a different choice at i i guess the the main thing in terms of a different choice is that i wish i had gotten some blow my camera somebody else get a picture of me standing in front of the
the statute, the Gossett democracy.
I was going to have all three of us, myself and our two kids, do that.
Of course, now that opportunity is gone.
Some people ask, why didn't you go back down to the square?
Why didn't you try to see what was going on?
And I realized that that would be a very foolish thing to do.
And I still think that I made the right decision.
Once the violence broke out,
I realized even though it was not directed towards foreigners, if I just happened to be in the wrong place at the wrong time, they were going to stop shooting because, oh, there goes a foreigner.
We don't want to shoot him.
So I think that I made the right decision there.
OK. And then lastly, you shared about the camera.
So you had that as visual images of where you had been.
When you got back to College Station,
I know you had shared with me an article you wrote called China's Pro-Democracy Movement.
Did you make any other written records or journal accounts?
Well, when I got back, I was one of the first Americans who'd been to Tiananmen Square and who had come back.
So a lot of the news media was interested in
hearing what I had to say.
One of the TV stations in Houston was at the airport when I got there, and I had a radio station in that calling.
And it upset me in that the main thing they were interested in was how many bodies did you see, a body count, and how much blood was there.
Not really in terms of what was going on, what was the significance of this thing, and what was really happening.
Of course, my body clock, my biological clock was off.

I got back here Wednesday, and Thursday morning, I guess about 3 o'clock in the morning, I was, I woke up and couldn't go back to sleep, and so I went into my den and wrote up a short article that was later printed by several papers in Houston and
San Antonio and Austin, around the state and some other states, kind of pulling together in a relatively short form of what I had seen.
And then over the summer, because I'd given some talks in that and found out more, kind of tried to make some sense for myself as to what I was going on, what had happened, what led up to the
demonstration of what happened there and what was going on in China over the summer.
And then I ended up with the six-page paper that I sent you.

But newspapers aren't arrested in things that are that long or that detailed, so it's more for personal use in reminding me and giving to friends who were arrested, you know, what was really happening, what was going on.

When you say the newspapers, for example, did the local newspaper here in College Station interested in your work, or was it only... Yeah, both the local newspaper and the local TV station, they came out.
Again, the first question was, you know, how many bodies did you see, how many people did you see killed?
And even though I told them that I did not see anybody killed on that, still in the newspaper article,
There was some mention that I'd seen some people shot.
I want to give them the benefit of the doubt.
They tried the best they could to take a relatively long interview and get the gist of what was going on.
But I guess they think they've got to make it interesting to the viewers and the readers, so they've got to get some of that type of stuff in there.
I wouldn't give them the doubt.
It was an honest effort, honest mistake.
They weren't deliberately trying to twist what I had said into something that I hadn't.
Lastly, one last question in terms of do you hope to go back to China any time in the near future?
If the opportunity arises, I would love to be able to go back.
As long as the current regime is in, I don't know if they will let me go back.
I've been rather
vocal about what I saw.
I felt that was something that I owed to the people in Tiananmen Square.
And like I said, there were more people who were killed outside of the square than were killed in the square.
I'm convinced that the accurate count is more around 2,000 or 3,000 than what some people are putting around as a couple of hundred, to let the world know what happened in the square.
if I apply for a visa, the Chinese government might not let me go back.
But if they do, I think I would be, it would be safe.
I don't think they're going to haul me off and throw me in jail if they let me go back.
Of course, I'd have to be very careful about what I said and what I did while I was there, but I would not give them any excuse.
And I said, if the modern element gains control after Deng Xiaoping's death and continues the reforms and opening up,
I think it would be safe.
And I would like to go back and be able to see what changes have taken place.
And I know my two older kids were really disappointed that they didn't get to go and want to go back there.
So if an opportunity arises, we'll try to get there.
You would consider going back with the family?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
OK.
Thank you very much for sharing with us today about your
in China at a time that were very volatile, but of which the Western world is very interested in knowing about.
Thank you again.
